Following in the steps of #145, this PR redesigns the server API to move as much Conjure-specific behavior as possible into the generated code. The interface exposed to server implementations is simply a map from `Request` to `Response`.

One downside of the current interface is that you basically need an adapter layer to map `Result<Response, Error>` to `Response` since otherwise you can't just use `?` to propagate errors in a handler. Part of the awkwardness here is that we want `SafeParams` to be filled out even if the request fails. A possible alternate approach could be:

```rust
pub trait Endpoint<I, O>: EndpointMetadata {
    fn handle(&self, req: Request<I>, safe_params: &mut SafeParams) -> Result<Response<ResponseBody<O>, Error>;
}
```

It is unfortunate that we need to add this extra argument, but seems less bad than having some kind of interior-mutable extension in the request that you'd poke the safe params into. This also makes the server implementation responsible for encoding error responses, but we could provide a public API for that so you could just do something like

```rust
let mut safe_params = SafeParams::new();
let response = handler.handle(req, &mut safe_params)
    .unwrap_or_else(conjure_http::server::encode_error_response);
```

Like the previous PR, most of the line count is just regenerating the checked in code.

Closes #122
